            "title": "Micron buoyed by explosive demand, despite market jitters",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text article-text--clear\"><p>The memory chip specialist remains at the heart of the current artificial intelligence momentum, driven by sustained demand for DRAM and NAND, as well as the arrival of next-generation memory such as HBM4. In this context, Micron reported adjusted EPS of $12.20, well above the $9.31 expected. Revenue reached $23.86bn, above the consensus of $20.07bn. Year-on-year, revenues nearly tripled from $8.05bn in the same period last year.<br/><br/><b>Outlook remains highly favorable<br/></b><br/>The group anticipates this momentum will continue, with revenue of approximately $33.5bn for the current quarter, representing an increase of more than 200% y-o-y. Adjusted EPS is expected at $19.15, again significantly above market forecasts.<br/><br/>Net income also rose sharply, reaching $13.8bn compared to $1.58bn a year earlier. To support this growth, Micron announced a $5bn increase in capex to expand production capacity. This strategy mirrors those of its competitors, notably Samsung and SK Hynix, amid persistent supply constraints.<br/><br/><b>Short-term concerns over investment levels<br/></b><br/>However, this increase in investment comes amid growing questions regarding the AI sector's ability to generate sustainable profits. These announcements cooled investor sentiment, leading to a mid-session decline in the share price.<br/><br/>Despite this short-term reaction, several analysts remain confident in Micron's prospects. Vijay Rakesh, an analyst at Mizuho Securities, raised his estimates and maintained his \"outperform\" rating, with a price target increased to $530. He believes the group benefits from a solid positioning, with strong profitability and robust roadmaps in the DRAM and NAND segments.<br/><br/>Meanwhile, Harlan Sur, a hardware specialist at JP Morgan, sought to downplay fears of a potential slowdown in margin growth. According to him, \"the key point remains the sustainability of these margin levels: the structural supply constraints supporting current prices are not expected to be resolved by the arrival of new capacity before the end of 2028.\"</p></div>",
            "link": "https://hk.marketscreener.com/news/micron-buoyed-by-explosive-demand-despite-market-jitters-ce7e5ededf81f427",
            "pub_date": "2026-03-20 00:11:44",
